:"1500","1489":"1489","1400":"1400","1422":"1422","1455":"1455","1488":"1488","1367":"1367","1366":"1366","1397":"1397","about 1367":"about 1367","March 1397":"March 1397","31 December 1488":"31 December 1488","1329":"1329","Warwick, Warwickshire, England":"Warwick, Warwickshire, England","Lawrence Lydiard, Somersetshire, England":"Somerset, England","Mappowder, Dorset, England, United Kingdom":"Mappowder, Dorset, England, United Kingdom","Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Coker, Dorset, , England":"Dorset, England, United Kingdom","Mappowder, Dorset, England":"Mappowder, Dorset, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Coker","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["see   Cocker  .","habitational name from a group of villages in Somerset named with Coker, from a Celtic river name meaning ‘crooked’.","English (southeastern):"],"variants":[{"name":"Coaker","meanings":["English (Devon): variant of   Coker  ."]},{"name":"Cocker","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): nickname for a quarrelsome person, from Middle English <i>coker</i> ‘fighter, wrangler’.","English: occupational name, ‘one who puts up hay in cocks’, a seasonal occupation.","Probably an Americanized form of German   Kocher  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":15,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":88,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Robert Coker was born about 1367, in Mappowder, Dorset, England, United Kingdom, his father, John Coker de Worle, was 41 and his mother, Eleanor de la Veale, was 40. He had at least 2 sons with Elizabeth Turgis. He died on 31 December 1488, in Mappowder, Dorset, England, at the age of 122."},"et":{"about 1367–31 December 1488":"umbes 1367–31. detsember 1488","1367–1488":"1367–1488","1370–Female":"1370–Surnud","1401–1489":"1401–1489","1422–1500":"1422–1500","1327–1400":"1327–1400","1329–1397":"1329–1397","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1327":"1327","1401":"1401","1500":"1500","1489":"1489","1400":"1400","1422":"1422